{{for|the legislative body|National Assembly of the Republic of Poland}} {{one source|date=July 2012}}
"'''Polish parliament'''" ([[Swedish language|Swedish]] and [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]: ''Polsk riksdag''; {{lang-da|Polsk rigsdag}}; {{lang-de|Polnischer Reichstag}}; {{lang-nl|Poolse landdag}}; {{lang-pl|Polski parlament}}; {{lang-fi|Puolalainen parlamentti}}) is an expression referring to the historical [[Sejm walny|Polish parliaments (''Sejm walny'')]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I2IhmyMpcuYC&pg=PA389 |title=Building Capitalism: The Transformation of the Former Soviet Bloc |last=Åslund |first=Anders |authorlink=Anders Åslund |year=2002 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |page=389 |ISBN=0-521-80525-2 |accessdate=2010-01-10}}</ref> It implies [[wikt:chaos|chaos]] and general disorder, and that no real decision can be reached during sessions.
== Origin ==
Every single member of the Polish parliament during the 17th and 18th century had an absolute [[veto]] ({{lang-la|[[liberum veto]]}}); as a result, legislation could only be passed [[unanimity|unanimously]]. Originally, the procedure was used for technical issues such as [[Point of order|points of order]], but as diverging interests discovered they could disrupt their opponents' agendas singlehandedly, the process came to be abused. Today, the expression is mostly used to describe an assembly that is too easy for minorities or individuals to disrupt and/or has too many parties present for meaningful and orderly debate and decision-making to take place. The expression is found in several European languages, including all [[Scandinavian languages]].
