'''Thomas Richards''' (c. 1710 &ndash; 20 March 1790) was a Welsh curate from [[Coychurch]] in the eighteenth century, best known for his 1753 ''Thesaurus'', a [[Welsh language|Welsh]]-[[English language|English]] dictionary.<ref>Prys Morgan, p. 43 in ''The Invention of Tradition'' (1992), [[Eric J. Hobsbawm]], Terence O. Ranger (editors); [https://books.google.com/books?id=sfvnNdVY3KIC&pg=PA43 Google Books].</ref> The Welsh-English dictionary was used by Dr. [[Samuel Johnson]] in compiling ''[[A Dictionary of the English Language]]'' (1755).<ref>{{cite book|editor=Hill, George Birkbeck|editorlink=George Birkbeck Norman Hill|title=Boswell's Life of Johnson|volume=vol. 1 (of 6)|location=Oxford|publisher=Clarendon Press|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=hvd.32044058222035;view=1up;seq=224|year=1887|page=186}}</ref> ==Life== Born about 1710 in [[Glamorganshire]], served for forty years the curacy of Coychurch (Llan Grallo) and [[Coety]] in that county. Richards died on 20 March 1790.<ref name=DNB>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Richards, Thomas (1710?-1790)}}</ref>
==Works== In 1746 Richards published a Welsh translation of a tract on the ''Cruelties and Persecutions of the Church of Rome'', by [[Philip Morant]]. His major work was ''Antiquæ Linguæ Britannicæ Thesaurus'', Bristol, 1753, a Welsh-English Dictionary, with a Welsh grammar prefixed, dedicated to [[Frederick, Prince of Wales]]. Based mainly on the work of [[John Davies (Mallwyd)|John Davies]] and [[Edward Llwyd]], his dictionary was fuller than any which had yet appeared.<ref name=DNB/> Other sources were [[William Wotton]] and [[Richard Morris (Welsh scholar)|Richard Morris]].<ref name=ODNB>{{ODNBweb|id=23540|title=Richards, Thomas|first=Richard|last=Crowe}}</ref> It has been suggested that Richards borrowed manuscripts from [[John Bradford (poet)|John Bradford]].<ref>[http://iolomorganwg.wales.ac.uk/pobl-johnbradford.php iolomorganwg.wales.ac.uk page, ''John Bradford (1706-85)''].</ref> A second edition appeared at [[Trefriw]] in 1815, a third in the same year at [[Dolgellau]], and a fourth at [[Merthyr Tydfil]] in 1838.<ref name=DNB/>
Richards was credited with work on the 1812 edition of [[William Evans (lexicographer)|William Evans]]'s English-Welsh dictionary.<ref name=ODNB/>
